  TkIn — in keyword
  TkWhile — while keyword
  TkLoop — loop keyword
  TkBreak — break keyword
  TkContinue — continue keyword
  TkReturn — return keyword
  TkMut — mut keyword
  TkConst — const keyword
  TkDefer — defer keyword
  TkWith — with keyword
  TkCatch — catch keyword
  TkTest — test keyword
  TkAssert — assert keyword
  TkDerives — derives keyword
  TkWhere — where keyword
  TkAs — as keyword
  TkIs — is keyword
  TkSelf — self keyword
  TkSelfType — Self keyword
  TkSpawn — spawn keyword
  TkScope — scope keyword
  TkSelect — select keyword
  TkBench — bench keyword
  TkBefore — before keyword
  TkAfter — after keyword
  TkYield — yield keyword
  TkMock — mock keyword
  TkExtern — extern keyword
  TkPlus — +
  TkMinus — -
  TkStar — *
  TkSlash — /
  TkPercent — %
  TkAmpersand — &
  TkPipe — |
  TkCaret — ^
  TkTilde — ~
  TkBang — !
  TkLShift — <<
  TkRShift — >>
  TkEqEq — ==
  TkBangEq — !=
  TkLt — <
  TkGt — >
  TkLtEq — <=
  TkGtEq — >=
  TkAmpAmp — &&
  TkPipePipe — ||
  TkDotDot — ..
  TkDotDotEq — ..=
  TkPipeGt — |>
  TkQuestion — ?
  TkQuestionDot — ?.
  TkQuestionQuestion — ??
  TkArrow — ->
  TkFatArrow — =>
  TkLParen — (
  TkRParen — )
  TkLBracket — [
  TkRBracket — ]
  TkLBrace — {
  TkRBrace — }
  TkComma — ,
  TkColon — :
  TkDot — .
  TkDotLBrace — .{
  TkAt — @
  TkEq — =
  TkColonEq — :=
  TkNewline — Newline (statement terminator)
  TkEof — End of file
  TkIllegal — Unrecognized token
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 12
@purpose Discriminates every distinct token the lexer can produce. Variants cover literals, all 44 keywords (including concurrency keywords reserved for future use), operators, punctuation, assignment, and special markers (newline, EOF, illegal).
@notes TkBoolTrue/TkBoolFalse are keyword variants, not literal variants — `true` and `false` go through lookup_keyword. TkStringStart/TkStringMiddle/TkStringEnd form a triple for string interpolation; a non-interpolated string uses TkStringLit instead. TkDotLBrace is declared but never emitted by the current lexer.
@antipatterns Do not compare TokenKind values with == directly; the sum type lacks derived equality. Use kind_eq() which compares via token_name strings. [src: token.aria:335]

---

@type Token
@kind struct
@fields
  kind: TokenKind — Token classification
  text: str — Source text of the token
  line: i64 — 1-based line number
  col: i64 — 1-based column number
  offset: i64 — Byte offset into source
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 124
@purpose Carries a classified token with its source location. The text field holds the literal value for string/char tokens (with escape sequences already resolved), not the raw source text.
@invariants line >= 1, col >= 1, offset >= 0. For TkStringLit/TkCharLit, text contains the decoded value (e.g., actual newline character, not "\n").
@notes For TkStringStart/TkStringMiddle/TkStringEnd, text holds the string content between interpolation boundaries with escapes resolved.

---

@type Lexer
@kind struct
@fields
  source: str — Full source text
  file: str — Source file path
  pos: i64 — Current byte position
  line: i64 — Current line number
  col: i64 — Current column number
  tokens: [Token] — Accumulated tokens
  diagnostics: DiagnosticBag — Accumulated diagnostics
  paren_depth: i64 — Parenthesis nesting depth
  bracket_depth: i64 — Bracket nesting depth
  brace_depth: i64 — Brace nesting depth
  interp_depth: i64 — String interpolation nesting depth
  interp_brace_depth: i64 — Brace depth within interpolation
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 49
@purpose Immutable lexer state threaded through all scanning functions. Each function returns a new Lexer with updated position, tokens, and/or diagnostics rather than mutating in place.
@invariants
  tokens always has at least one element (sentinel TkEof at index 0, inserted by new_lexer).
  paren_depth, bracket_depth, brace_depth >= 0 (guarded by > 0 checks before decrement).
  interp_depth tracks how many nested string interpolations are active; interp_brace_depth records the brace_depth at the point interpolation began, so the lexer knows which } ends the interpolation vs. a normal block.
@notes The functional style (returning new structs) is dictated by Aria's immutability-by-default semantics. The `mut lex` binding in tokenize rebinds to successive states.

