@fn new_token
@sig (kind: TokenKind, text: str, line: i64, col: i64, offset: i64) -> Token
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 132
@purpose Constructs a Token with all fields. Simple factory function.

---

@fn token_name
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> str
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 137
@purpose Maps every TokenKind variant to its display string. Keywords return their lowercase source text (e.g., "fn"), operators return their symbol (e.g., "<="), and special tokens return uppercase names (e.g., "IDENT", "EOF", "ILLEGAL").
@notes Used pervasively: by kind_eq for equality comparison, by is_keyword for keyword detection, by terminates_statement for newline insertion, and by diagnostic rendering. Exhaustive match over all ~100 variants. [src: token.aria:137-238]

---

@fn lookup_keyword
@sig (text: str) -> TokenKind
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 242
@purpose Resolves an identifier string to its keyword TokenKind, or TkIdent if it is not a keyword. Called by _scan_ident after consuming an alphanumeric run.
@post Returns TkIdent for any text that is not one of the 44 reserved keywords or `true`/`false`.
@notes Implemented as a linear chain of if-return statements. `true` and `false` map to TkBoolTrue/TkBoolFalse respectively. `Self` (capitalized) maps to TkSelfType. [src: token.aria:242-288]

---

@fn is_keyword
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> bool
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 290
@purpose Determines whether a TokenKind is a keyword by checking if token_name starts with a lowercase letter.
@notes Returns true for TkBoolTrue ("true") and TkBoolFalse ("false") since those display names start with lowercase. Returns false for TkSelfType because "Self" starts with uppercase. This heuristic works because all operator/punctuation display names start with symbols and all special tokens (IDENT, EOF, etc.) start with uppercase. [src: token.aria:290-302]

---

@fn terminates_statement
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> bool
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 307
@purpose Determines whether a newline after this token kind should be treated as a statement terminator (TkNewline). This implements Aria's semicolon-free syntax — only newlines after "completing" tokens become statement boundaries.
@notes Terminating tokens: identifiers, all literal types, true/false, STRING_END, break/continue/return, closing delimiters ), ], }, ?, !, self, Self. Notably, operators and opening delimiters do NOT terminate — allowing multi-line expressions. Uses kind_eq for TkRBrace check since "}" contains an escape sequence that doesn't match via string comparison. [src: token.aria:307-332]
@antipatterns Adding a new literal or closing-bracket token without updating this function will cause newline insertion failures, leading to parse errors on multi-statement code.

---

@fn kind_eq
@sig (a: TokenKind, b: TokenKind) -> bool
@source_file src/lexer/token.aria
@source_line 335
@purpose Compares two TokenKind values for equality by comparing their token_name strings, since Aria sum types do not have derived == support in the bootstrap compiler.
@notes This is a workaround for a bootstrap compiler limitation. Once the self-hosting compiler supports derived Eq on sum types, this function can be replaced with direct == comparison. [src: token.aria:335-336]

---

@fn new_lexer
@sig (source: str, file: str) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 69
@purpose Creates a fresh Lexer state positioned at the start of source, with a sentinel TkEof token at index 0.
@post tokens has exactly one element (sentinel). pos=0, line=1, col=1. All depth counters are 0.
@notes The sentinel token at index 0 simplifies _last_token_kind — it can always return a valid TokenKind without checking for an empty list. The sentinel is effectively invisible since the final TkEof appended by tokenize is what consumers use. [src: lexer.aria:63-77]

---

@fn tokenize
@sig (source: str, file: str) -> Lexer
@calls [new_lexer, _scan_ident, _scan_number, _scan_string, _scan_char, _scan_raw_string, _scan_triple_string, _scan_comment]
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 518
@purpose Main entry point: tokenizes an entire source string into a complete token list. Returns the final Lexer state containing all tokens and any diagnostics.
@pre source is a complete Aria source file. file is the path used for diagnostic locations.
@post Returned Lexer.tokens starts with sentinel TkEof, contains all scanned tokens, and ends with a final TkEof. Diagnostics bag contains any lexer errors encountered.
@effects Allocates tokens list and diagnostics bag. No I/O.
@workflow Called by the parser (or CLI) as the first compilation step. The returned tokens are extracted via get_tokens and fed to the parser.
@notes
  Main loop dispatches on first character with single-character lookahead (_peek_next).
  Newline insertion: only emits TkNewline when (a) not inside parens/brackets and (b) the previous token terminates a statement. Braces do NOT suppress newlines — only parens and brackets do. [src: lexer.aria:596]
  String interpolation: when `{` is found inside a string, emits TkStringStart (or TkStringMiddle), increments interp_depth, saves current brace_depth, and returns to the main loop. When `}` matches the saved brace_depth, decrements interp_depth and calls _scan_string_impl(true) to continue the string.
  Raw string detection: `r` followed by `"` or `#` triggers _scan_raw_string; otherwise falls through to _scan_ident. [src: lexer.aria:607-614]
  Triple-quoted string detection: checks three consecutive `"` characters. [src: lexer.aria:620-635]
  Operator disambiguation uses single-character lookahead: `-` vs `->`, `=` vs `==` vs `=>`, `.` vs `..` vs `..=`, etc.
  Unrecognized characters produce both an E0001 diagnostic and a TkIllegal token. [src: lexer.aria:801-803]

