@fn _last_token_kind
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> TokenKind
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 215
@purpose Returns the kind of the most recently added token, or TkEof if only the sentinel exists. Used by newline insertion logic to determine whether the previous token terminates a statement.
@notes The sentinel TkEof at index 0 means this function never fails on an empty-looking list — tokens always has length >= 1. [src: lexer.aria:220-225]

---

@fn _scan_ident
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 225
@purpose Scans an identifier or keyword. Consumes alphanumeric characters (including underscore), then calls lookup_keyword to determine if the text is a reserved word.
@pre Current character is alphabetic or underscore (_is_alpha).
@post One token added: either a keyword token or TkIdent.

---

@fn _scan_number
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 237
@purpose Scans a numeric literal: decimal integers, hex (0x), octal (0o), binary (0b), floats (with optional exponent), duration suffixes (ns, us, ms, s, m, h), and size suffixes (b, kb, mb, gb). Underscores are allowed as digit separators in all bases.
@pre Current character is a digit.
@post One token added: TkIntLit, TkFloatLit, TkDurationLit, or TkSizeLit.
@notes
  Float detection: requires a digit after the dot to distinguish `42.0` (float) from `42..` (int followed by range operator). [src: lexer.aria:290-292]
  Duration suffix `m` alone means minutes; `ms` means milliseconds. The code checks _peek_next to disambiguate. [src: lexer.aria:334-341]
  Size suffix `b` alone means bytes; requires that the next character is not alphanumeric to avoid consuming the `b` in an identifier like `0bad`. [src: lexer.aria:364-371]
  Duration and size suffixes are only checked for integer literals (is_float == false). [src: lexer.aria:312]

---

@fn _scan_char
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 350
@purpose Scans a character literal ('x' or '\n' etc.). Resolves escape sequences to their actual character values.
@pre Current character is a single quote '.
@post One TkCharLit token added. The text field contains the decoded character value, not the raw source.
@notes Supported escapes: \n, \t, \r, \\, \', \0. Unrecognized escapes pass through the escaped character verbatim. Does not produce an error diagnostic for missing closing quote — just stops scanning. [src: lexer.aria:383-399]

---

@fn _scan_string
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 367
@purpose Entry point for scanning a regular (non-raw, non-triple) string literal. Delegates to _scan_string_impl with is_continuation=false.
@pre Current character is a double quote ".

---

@fn _scan_string_impl
@sig (lex: Lexer, is_continuation: bool) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 371
@purpose Core string scanner that handles both initial strings and continuation after interpolation expressions. Resolves escape sequences and detects interpolation boundaries.
@pre If is_continuation is false, current character is ". If true, current character is the first character after the closing } of an interpolation expression.
@post Adds one of: TkStringLit (complete non-interpolated string), TkStringStart (string before first interpolation), TkStringMiddle (string between interpolations), or TkStringEnd (string after last interpolation).
@errors E0002 "unterminated string literal" — if end of input or newline is reached before closing ".
@notes
  Escape sequences: \n, \r, \t, \\, \", \0, \{, \}. The \{ and \} escapes prevent interpolation. [src: lexer.aria:440-443]
  Interpolation: when an unescaped { is found, the function emits a TkStringStart or TkStringMiddle, increments interp_depth, saves the current brace_depth to interp_brace_depth, and returns immediately. The main tokenize loop then scans the interpolation expression normally until the matching } is found. [src: lexer.aria:448-459]
  Newlines inside strings are not allowed (produces E0002). Use triple-quoted strings for multi-line content. [src: lexer.aria:460-462]

---

@fn _scan_raw_string
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 441
@purpose Scans a raw string literal (r"..." or r#"..."# with arbitrary hash counts). No escape processing — all characters are literal.
@pre Current character is 'r', next is '"' or '#'.
@post One TkRawStringLit token added. Text contains the raw content without delimiters.
@errors E0002 "expected '\"' after r-string prefix" — if no opening quote found after r and optional hashes.
@notes The closing delimiter must be " followed by exactly the same number of # characters as the opening. The scanner uses a lookahead loop to verify hash count matches before accepting the close. [src: lexer.aria:506-521]

---

@fn _scan_triple_string
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 477
@purpose Scans a triple-quoted string literal ("""..."""). Skips an optional newline immediately after the opening delimiter. Handles embedded newlines.
@pre Current character is the first " of a """ sequence.
@post One TkTripleStringLit token added. Text contains content with newlines preserved.
@notes Comment in source mentions auto-dedentation but it is not implemented — the token text contains the raw indented content. A leading newline after """ is stripped. [src: lexer.aria:571-573]

---

@fn _scan_comment
@sig (lex: Lexer) -> Lexer
@source_file src/lexer/lexer.aria
@source_line 518
@purpose Skips a line comment (// to end of line). Does not produce any token — comments are discarded.
@pre Current position is at the first / of a // sequence.
@post Lexer advanced to the \n (not past it — the main loop handles the newline). No tokens added.
@notes Only line comments are supported. Aria has no block comments. [src: lexer.aria:578-584]
